## Sources of truth

- **Movement identity, thesis, strategy, principles:** `movement/SPEC.md`
- **Product spec, features, technical decisions:** `products/social-v2/SPEC.md`

Always read the relevant SPEC before making significant changes.

## Non-negotiable constraints

These are core principles of the movement. Never suggest changes that violate them:

- **No comments, no likes, no DMs, no reactions. Ever.** Feedback happens in person.
- **No payments on the platform.** Business happens between humans.
- **Community-first entry.** QR code + secret password spoken in person. No browse, no discover page.
- **Cooperative ownership.** Each city is a cooperative (SC). Members vote by role.
- **Open source. Aggregate, don't build.** If someone built a great tool, integrate it.
- **Anyone can start one. Anyone can build one.** The technical barrier is gone.

## Tone of voice

Warm, direct, slightly rebellious. Anti-corporate but not angry. "Your neighbor who has a crazy idea and you believe them." Never corporate jargon, never startup-speak.

## Key context

- **GPFC srl** is the permanent engine, not temporary scaffolding
- **Transition Towns** is the direct blueprint — Rob Hopkins is the first strategic contact
- **The website** is a movement pitch deck, not a product page
- **The products are demos**, not the movement itself — each one proves a different face of what a Grassroot Hopper can build
- **Contributors get co-op shares**, not money — no freelance contracts, no bounties
- **Domains:** grassroothopper.com, .org, .eu, .be — the net that catches enthusiasts
